Conditional statements let your program make decisions. They follow the same logic you use every day: "IF this condition is true, THEN do this action. OTHERWISE, do something else."

JavaScript syntax:
if (condition) {
  // do this if the condition is true
} else if (anotherCondition) {
  // do this if the first condition is false but this one is true
} else {
  // do this if all conditions are false
}

Real-world example — a quiz grading system:
let score = 4;
if (score >= 4) {
  console.log("Excellent! You passed with distinction.");
} else if (score >= 3) {
  console.log("Good job! You passed the module.");
} else {
  console.log("Keep studying. You need at least 3 to pass.");
}

Comparison operators you will use:
- === means "is equal to" (let passed = score === 5)
- !== means "is not equal to"
- > means "greater than"
- < means "less than"
- >= means "greater than or equal to"
- <= means "less than or equal to"

Conditionals are the foundation of all programming logic. Every app, game, and website uses them constantly.

LOOPS execute a block of code multiple times. Instead of writing the same code 10 times, you write it once and let the loop repeat it:

// Print numbers 1 to 5
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  console.log("Module " + i);
}
// Output: Module 1, Module 2, Module 3, Module 4, Module 5

// Loop through an array
let cities = ["Accra", "Kumasi", "Tamale", "Takoradi"];
for (let i = 0; i < cities.length; i++) {
  console.log("I love " + cities[i]);
}

FUNCTIONS are reusable blocks of code that perform a specific task. Instead of repeating code, you define it once and call it whenever you need it:

function greetStudent(name) {
  return "Welcome to Pool of Grace, " + name + "!";
}

console.log(greetStudent("Ama"));    // "Welcome to Pool of Grace, Ama!"
console.log(greetStudent("Kwame"));  // "Welcome to Pool of Grace, Kwame!"

Functions make your code organized, reusable, and easier to debug. Professional developers write dozens of functions every day. If you find yourself writing the same code twice, that code should probably be a function.

A responsive website automatically adjusts its layout to look great on any screen size — mobile phones, tablets, and desktop computers. In Ghana, over 70% of internet users access the web primarily through mobile phones, so mobile-responsive design is not optional — it is essential.

CSS Media Queries are the primary tool for responsive design. They let you apply different styles based on the screen size:

/* Default styles (mobile first) */
.container {
  width: 100%;
  padding: 10px;
}

/* Tablet and larger screens */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    width: 750px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}

/* Desktop screens */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    width: 960px;
  }
}

The "mobile first" approach means you design for small screens first, then add complexity for larger screens. This is the industry standard because it is easier to add features for bigger screens than to remove them for smaller ones.

Other responsive tools: Use percentages (width: 50%) instead of fixed pixels (width: 500px). Use CSS Flexbox for flexible layouts. Use max-width to prevent elements from getting too wide on large screens.

DOM stands for Document Object Model. It is the browser's internal representation of your HTML page as a tree of objects. JavaScript can access this tree and change anything on the page — text, colors, visibility, even add or remove entire elements.

Selecting elements:
const heading = document.getElementById("main-title");     // By ID
const buttons = document.querySelectorAll(".btn");           // By CSS class
const firstParagraph = document.querySelector("p");          // First matching element

Changing content:
heading.textContent = "Welcome, Ama!";                      // Change text
heading.style.color = "#006B3F";                             // Change style
heading.classList.add("highlighted");                        // Add a CSS class

Responding to events (clicks, typing, etc.):
const button = document.getElementById("submit-btn");
button.addEventListener("click", function() {
  alert("Form submitted! Medaase!");
});

DOM manipulation is what makes websites interactive. When you click a button and a dropdown appears, that is JavaScript manipulating the DOM. When you type in a search box and see suggestions appear, that is JavaScript reading your input and updating the DOM in real time.

Python is known for clean, readable syntax that resembles plain English. Unlike JavaScript which uses curly brackets and semicolons, Python uses indentation (spaces) to organize code. This makes Python code easier to read and write, especially for beginners.

Compare JavaScript vs Python for the same task:

JavaScript:
function greet(name) {
  if (name === "Ama") {
    console.log("Akwaaba, " + name + "!");
  } else {
    console.log("Hello, " + name + "!");
  }
}

Python:
def greet(name):
    if name == "Ama":
        print(f"Akwaaba, {name}!")
    else:
        print(f"Hello, {name}!")

Notice how Python is shorter and more readable. No curly brackets, no semicolons — just clean indentation.

Python is especially powerful for:
- DATA ANALYSIS: Analyzing agricultural data, sales records, or survey results
- AUTOMATION: Writing scripts to automate repetitive tasks (like renaming files or sending emails)
- WEB DEVELOPMENT: Building server-side applications using Django or Flask
- MOBILE MONEY ANALYTICS: Processing and analyzing mobile money transaction data

The SELECT statement is the most common SQL command. It retrieves data from a database table:

-- Get all students
SELECT * FROM students;

-- Get only names and cities
SELECT name, city FROM students;

-- Get students from Kumasi
SELECT * FROM students WHERE city = 'Kumasi';

-- Get enrolled students, sorted by name
SELECT * FROM students WHERE enrolled = true ORDER BY name;

-- Count how many students are enrolled
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM students WHERE enrolled = true;

-- Get students whose name contains "Ama"
SELECT * FROM students WHERE name LIKE '%Ama%';

The WHERE clause filters results based on conditions. You can combine conditions:
SELECT * FROM students WHERE city = 'Accra' AND enrolled = true;
SELECT * FROM students WHERE city = 'Kumasi' OR city = 'Accra';

Practical tip: SQL keywords (SELECT, FROM, WHERE) are typically written in uppercase for readability, but they work in lowercase too.

CRUD stands for Create, Read, Update, and Delete — the four fundamental operations for managing data in any database:

CREATE (INSERT) — Adding new data:
INSERT INTO students (name, email, city, enrolled)
VALUES ('Abena Osei', 'abena@email.com', 'Cape Coast', true);

READ (SELECT) — Retrieving data:
SELECT * FROM students WHERE city = 'Cape Coast';

UPDATE — Modifying existing data:
UPDATE students SET city = 'Accra' WHERE id = 3;
UPDATE students SET enrolled = true WHERE name = 'Efua Darko';

DELETE — Removing data:
DELETE FROM students WHERE id = 3;

IMPORTANT: Always use a WHERE clause with UPDATE and DELETE! Without it, you will modify or delete ALL rows in the table:
-- DANGEROUS: This updates EVERY student's city!
UPDATE students SET city = 'Accra';  -- Missing WHERE clause!

-- SAFE: This only updates one specific student
UPDATE students SET city = 'Accra' WHERE id = 3;

This is one of the most common mistakes beginners make, and it can have serious consequences in a production database. Always double-check your WHERE clause before running UPDATE or DELETE.

Modern web applications use "state" to track data that changes over time. In React (which Pool of Grace uses), state is managed with hooks:

const [name, setName] = useState("");
const [email, setEmail] = useState("");
const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false);

A form handler captures user input and sends it to the server:

const handleSubmit = async () => {
  // Validate inputs
  if (!name || !email) {
    alert("Please fill in all fields");
    return;
  }

  // Send data to the backend
  const response = await axios.post("/api/register", {
    name: name,
    email: email
  });

  // Handle the response
  if (response.data.success) {
    setSubmitted(true);
    alert("Registration successful!");
  }
};

Axios is a popular JavaScript library for making HTTP requests from the frontend to the backend. It handles the communication between the client and server, converting data to JSON format automatically.

State management is crucial because web pages need to remember things: Is the user logged in? What items are in their cart? Which form fields have they filled out? State answers all these questions.
